noun.description: That which is thrown out; an ejection or emission; output or production.
An act or the action of throwing something out; an instance of this.

verb.description: Chiefly poetic. To throw or thrust out or outwards; to cast out or expel. Now usually in pass.
To surpass in throwing; to throw further than.

origin: Mid 16th century; earliest use found in Usk's Testament of Loue. From out- + throw, after to throw out or out-throw<br>late Middle English; earliest use found in John Gower (d. 1408), poet. From out- + throw.
